rs aids those looking to excuse or endorse key events of national history by implying that they were destined to happen. She challenges the reputations of Langland, Gower, and Chaucer as prophets of the Protestant Reformation, Richard II’s deposition, and secular Humanism, respectively. This intellectual and critical assessment of medieval authors and their works successfully makes the case that prophecy emerged and recurred as an important theme in medieval authorial self-representations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aEnglish literatureyMiddle English, 1100-1500xHistory and criticism. 0aPolitics in literature. 0aProphecy in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aCanterbury Tales.  aChristine de Pizan.  aEustache Deschamps.  aGeoffrey Chaucer.  aHenry IV.  aJohn Gower.  aRicardian authors.  aRichard II.  aThe House of Fame.  aWilliam Langland.  amedieval authorship.  aprophecy.  areception.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076715540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487563486423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487563486/original  a978-3-11-076715-5  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK